Pleiades Change Log: 2022-09-01 - 2022-09-31

New Place Resources

  • Alfar Romano de Cartuja
    The Alfar Romano de Cartuja (Roman potters' workshop of Cartuja) was a pottery production center for southern Spain that was active from the 1st century till the later 2nd century CE.
    Creators: David Rothfels; Julia Doelling
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Thomas Landvatter
  • Ancient Theater of Argos
    The Ancient Theater of Argos was a Hellenistic theater initially constructed in 320 BCE and later renovated by the Romans.
    Creators: Merrick Gormley; Nomi Solwren
    Contributors: Thomas Landvatter
  • Arch of Caracalla
    The Arch of Caracalla at Volubilis was constructed in 217 CE by the governor Marcus Aurelius Sebastenus in honor of the emperor Caracalla and his mother Domna Julia.
    Creators: Alisa MacDonald; Anna Wilson
    Contributors: Thomas Landvatter
  • Area di Monte Giulio e Capitaneria
    The low hill known as Monte Giulio is anthropic, formed by the accumulation of sediment atop an ancient quay. Archaeological investigation beginning in 1968 revealed numerous architectural remains, including a cistern and a bath complex along the via Guidoni. The ruins of the so-called Capitaneria, or Harbor office, are located near the modern stele to the Fallen of Kindu. This complex seems to have been connected to the management of port traffic and was in use from the reign of Claudius until the fourth century.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
  • Ascoli Satriano Roman bridge
    A Roman bridge crossing the Carapelle stream in the territory of Ascoli Satriano.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors: Tom Elliott
  • Barcola
    A no-longer-visible villa maritima was identified north of Tergeste in 1887. According to AdriAtlas, a reanalysis by Fontana (1993) places the beginnings of the villa's occupational sequence in the third quarter of the first century BCE.
    Creators: Francis Tassaux
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Tom Elliott
  • Bar Hill Fort Bathhouse
    The Bar Hill Fort Bathhouse was built around 140 CE, at the same time as the Antonine wall, and is a long and narrow stone structure with latrines and two heated rooms.
    Creators: Daphne Daniel; Rose Gatlin
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Thomas Landvatter
  • Casa del Marinaio
    A domus at Pompeii, the so-called Casa del Marinaio or Casa di Niobe or Casa del Gallo is linked to VII .15.1 and VII .15.16 and was excavated ca.1859 and 1871.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
  • Corviano
    Corviano (Bomarzo) is a protected landscape with evidence of Etruscan, Roman, and Medieval activity.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
  • Domus rustica
    The ruins of a Republican-period 'domus rustica' located on the via Alexandre Gustave Eiffel in Rome, Italy, near Ponte Galeria.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
  • Ecclesiasterion (Odeion) at Messene
    The Ecclesiasterion (Odeion) at Messene was originally constructed in the third century BCE and may be a converted ecclesiasterio/bouleuterion.
    Creators: Alisa MacDonald; Amir Wekseler
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Thomas Landvatter; Amir Weksler
  • Garšana
    A Babylonian town possibly located near Umma, Zabalam, and Karkar where over 1500 cuneiform tablets were found. The location of the site is unknown due to the tablets having been looted.
    Creators: Zachary Rosalinsky
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker
  • Ḥorvat Radum
    Small Iron Age fortress in the Northern Negev with a surrounding wall and three buildings making up the fortress.
    Creators: Zachary Rosalinsky
    Contributors:
  • Ḥorvat ʻUza
    Iron Age fortress in the Northern Negev Desert with a solid wall and ten towers. Inside the fortress are building complexes with streets between them.
    Creators: Zachary Rosalinsky
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker
  • House of Serenos at Trimithis
    Building B1 of Area 2.1 at Trimithis (Amheida) is a domus with an annexed stable dated to the 4th century CE.
    Creators: Gabriel Mckee
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker
  • House of the Skeleton
    The so-called "House of the Skeleton" was constructed in the early first century BCE in the Roman colony of Cosa. It stands an example of the domestic architecture of the Late Roman Republic.
    Creators: Celia Garb; George Crooks
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Thomas Landvatter
  • Ilıca (Ayas: cemetery)
    Cemetery site northwest of Ankara containing burials dated to the Hittite period (16th century BCE). The modern neighborhood of Ilıca is in the Ayas district of Turkey's Ankara province.
    Creators: Gabriel Mckee
    Contributors: Tom Elliott
  • Karban-I
    Burial site in the Northern Altai region containing remains associated with the Bulan-Koby culture (2nd-5th centuries CE).
    Creators: Gabriel Mckee
    Contributors:
  • Lake Mezzano
    Lake Mezzano is a small crater lake of central Italy that formed 400,000 years ago.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
  • Lefkandi Heroon(?)
    Rescue excavations in 1980 documented the remains of an unusual funerary structure dated ca. 1000 to 950 BCE that contained a double human burial alongside a horse burial. The structure's scale (50 by 13.8 m) and nature have led some scholars to identify it as a heroon.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors: Tom Elliott
  • Marigny à Fleurville Gallo-Roman Villa
    Remains of a Gallo-Roman Villa at modern Château de Marigny at Fleurville, France.
    Creators: Tom Elliott
    Contributors:
  • Mausoleum of Diocletian
    A mausoleum built to entomb Diocletian at his retirement palace that was constructed around 295 CE and is located in modern day Split, Croatia.
    Creators: Kiel Papa; Luka Bayon-Fraise
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Thomas Landvatter
  • Monumental Mid-Republican Building Complex
    This monumental complex of buildings at the city of Gabii was likely constructed in the mid-third century BCE as a public area for feasts, bathing, and ritual activities.
    Creators: AJ Adler; Shannon Well-Moran
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Thomas Landvatter; Shannon Wells-Moran
  • Odeon of Herodes Atticus
    A large theater in Athens, built during the Roman period on the south-western slope of the Acropolis around 160 to 174 CE.
    Creators: Kyle Nash; Ryan Dooley
    Contributors: Brady Kiesling; Jeffrey Becker; Thomas Landvatter
  • Odeon of Lyon
    The Odeon is a small theater in modern day Lyon, France built specifically for musical performances around the beginning of the 2nd century CE.
    Creators: Clara Leach; Elin Hansen
    Contributors: Thomas Landvatter
  • Phoenician cemetery at al-Bass
    Cemetery at the Al-Bass site in Tyre containing burials, funerary urns, and stelae dated to the Phoenician period (8th-6th century BCE).
    Creators: Gabriel Mckee
    Contributors:
  • Por(d)oselene (island)
    An island between Lesbos and Asia Minor, attested in multiple ancient sources and site of the homonymous city. The island has been identified with the modern Cunda Adası, Turkey.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker; Tom Elliott
    Contributors:
  • Posta Vecchia
    Remains of a Roman imperial villa incorporated into a post office that later became a hotel.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
  • Roman necropolis at al-Bass
    The Tyre necropolis, part of the UNESCO World Heritage site of Tyre, contains a triumphal arch and hundreds of stone sarcophagi dated to the Roman and Byzantine periods. It is located adjacent to an older Phoenician burial site.
    Creators: Gabriel Mckee
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker
  • Saint-Nizier-sous-Charlieu
    The site of a Gallo-Roman villa known since 1884.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
  • Salkhityn Am
    Cemetery site in northern Mongolia containing 35 burials dated to the Early Xiongnu period (200-50 BCE).
    Creators: Gabriel Mckee
    Contributors: Tom Elliott
  • Studforth Hill
    The remains of a Romano-British amphitheater were discovered on Studforth Hill, just outside the village of Aldborough between Harrogate and York in northern England.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
  • Tel 'Aroer
    Tell in the Negev desert with archaeological remains from an Iron Age town and a Hellenistic-early Roman settlement.
    Creators: Zachary Rosalinsky
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker
  • Tel Ḥarasim
    Tell in northern Israel with remains from the Late Bronze Age, Iron Age, Persian period, and Byzantine period. The tell was not fortified but did have a fortress in the Iron Age.
    Creators: Zachary Rosalinsky
    Contributors:
  • Tell Hazna I
    Religious and administrative center in Syria with two temple complexes. This site was in use in the Early Dynastic Period and the Uruk and Abaid periods.
    Creators: Zachary Rosalinsky
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker
  • Temple of Artemis Orthasia
    Remains of a sanctuary located on Mt. Kotilon northwest of the Bassai temple.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors: Brady Kiesling
  • Temple of Heracles
    The Temple of Heracles is one of the oldest temples in the Valley of the Temples in ancient Akragas, Sicily, dating from around the late 6th century BCE.
    Creators: Asta Rossi; Freya Schlaefer
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Thomas Landvatter
  • The Deir
    Monumental religious building carved out of rock in Petra, Jordan which was used for a variety of complex religious ceremonies and customs after the time of its completion in the mid-first century CE.
    Creators: Amir Weksler; Louise de Picciotto
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Thomas Landvatter
  • Tomb 3 (Tombs of the Kings)
    Tomb 3 is a rock-cut tomb with a peristyle courtyard in the "Tombs of the Kings" necropolis of Nea Paphos.
    Creators: Ariel Cooper; Matthew Redford
    Contributors: Tom Elliott; Thomas Landvatter
  • Tomb of Lucius Sepunius Sandilianus
    The Tomb of Lucius Sepunius Sandilianus is a Roman-period tomb, possibly of tholos typology, located in the Porta Nocera necropolis of Pompeii.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
  • Tombs of the Kings
    The "Tombs of the Kings" archaeological site is a Hellenistic and Roman-period necropolis associated with the city of Nea Paphos and characterized by large, rock-cut, subterranean tomb structures.
    Creators: Thomas Landvatter
    Contributors: Tom Elliott
  • Volna 1
    Site on the Kerch Strait inhabited from the 6th century BCE-4th century CE, and resettled in the 8th-9th, 12-13th, and 17th-18th centuries CE. Rescue excavations were conducted on the site from 1996-2012.
    Creators: Gabriel Mckee
    Contributors:

  • Alb(i)um Intimilium/Albintimilium
    Alb(i)um Intimilium/Albintimilium (modern Ventimiglia) was the main settlement of the Ligurian tribe of the Intemelii. In the 2nd century BC it came under control of the Roman Republic. Albintimilium became a municipium in 89 BC in the tribus Falerna. In the same period the city walls were built, with several towers. The city flourished in the early Imperial period, with baths, an acqueduct and a theater. In the 6th and early 7th century it was a Byzantine kastron, coming under control of the Longobards in 641. During the 7th and 8th century the Roman city was slowly abandoned in favour of a smaller hilltop settlement focused around the Cathedral.
    Creators: R. Häussler; S. Loseby
    Contributors: Brady Kiesling; Jeffrey Becker; Stefano Costa; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; DARMC; R. Talbert
    Modifications: modified Imagery location of archaeological area (update)
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker

  • Aulutrena
    A Roman castellum, located adjacent to the ancient settlement of Aporidos Come and the Aulutrene lake (modern Çapalı/Karakuyu in Turkey's Afyonkarahisar province). An initial (temporary?) camp on/near the location may have been established as early as the second century BC; however, archaeological and epigraphic evidence point to a small, stone-built installation with associated garrison, possibly during the Severan period that was later expanded in Byzantine times. The stone structure, at the modern town of Eldere, was heavily quarried and built over by the 1980s.
    Creators: C. Foss; S. Mitchell
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; DARMC; R. Talbert
    Modifications: edited; update deprecated place type; add vici.org 7432: Aulutrean
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker

  • Aulutrene/‘Aulocrene’ (lake)

  • Baliares/Gymnesiae Inss. (Maior et Minor)
    Baliares/Gymnesiae Inss. (Maior et Minor) (The Balearic Islands) is an island group of the western Mediterranean Sea, located to the east of the Iberian peninsula. In modern geographical terms, the four largest islands of the group are Majorca, Minorca, Ibiza, and Formentera, but the latter two are also part of the Pityussae island group of antiquity.

  • Bates’ (island)
    An island located in the East Lagoon of modern Marsa Matruh, Libya (ancient Paraetonium). Excavations on the island revealed evidence for a small shelter and/or revictualing station for ships' crews engaged in coastal trade during the late Bronze Age: a modest walled shelter as well as Minoan, Mycenaean, Cypriot, Canaanite, and Egyptian pottery. There is some minor archaeological evidence for subsequent periods, especially from the 8th century onward, but these are insufficient to gauge what sort of use(s) the island may have been put to during the pre-Roman and Roman periods (when Paraetonium occupied the entire southern shoreline of the lagoon.
    Creators: D.J. Mattingly
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Michael Heubel; Ryan Horne; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; R. Talbert; Richard Talbert
    Modifications: summary; added White 2002 vols 1 and 2; added access URI for White 1989; add summary; update title, references; created OSM location
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker; Tom Elliott

  • Boi(i)
    A later Iron Age Gallic tribe, the Boii enter Italy as part of the 'Gallic Invasion' of Italy in 390 BC. They made the Etruscan city of Felsina their new capital, Bononia (Bologna). The Romans defeated them decisively at Mutina.
    Creators: M. Pearce; P. Tozzi; R. Peretto
    Contributors: Brady Kiesling; Jeffrey Becker; Michael Heubel; Ryan Horne; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; R. Talbert; Richard Talbert
    Modifications: update references; created BAtlas Map Label Location

  • Borboros?

  • Caledonia (region)

  • Dur-Šarrukin Archive 2
    Two tiers of niches (similar to Dur-Šarrukin 1) were found in Room H 15 (on the northwestern side of Courtyard II) of the Nabû temple at Dur-Šarrukin, the short-lived capital of the Assyrian king Sargon II (721–705 BC). Although no inscribed objects were found inside the niches, the existence of a temple library is suggested by a similar construction in Room H 5 (on the northwestern side of Forecourt I). The empty niches might be the result of the move of the capital to Nineveh under Sennacherib (704–681 BC) or of the use of perishable writing materials.
    Creators: Thomas Seidler
    Contributors:
    Modifications: edited; edited; edited; edited; modified Plan location of Dur-Šarrukin Archive 2 (edited); modified name "Dur-Šarrukin Archive 2" (edited); modified connection "Dur-Šarrukin Archive 1" (edited)
    Actors: Thomas Seidler

  • Eremia Geton
    Strabo describes the Eremia Geton ("the wasteland/desolation of the Getai") as lying between the territory of the Getai and the Pontic Sea, between the river Ister (Danube) and the river Tyras (Dniester), a region where little ancient settlement has been found. This area, subject to the rising waters of the Black Sea, may also have been referred to by the name or descriptive term "Sorsdesertus" on the Peutinger Map.
    Creators: David Braund
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Michael Heubel; Ryan Horne; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; Diane Braund; R. Talbert; Richard Talbert
    Modifications: created BAtlas Map Label Location
    Actors: Brian Turner; Tom Elliott

  • Hilakku (region)
    Hilakku is a mountainous region near Tabālu and Que in the Cilician plain. Its exact location is still debated among scholars. Nevertheless, Hilakku has been tentatively identified as being in the area of Bolkar Dağları or in that of Göksu-Tal, in the western part of Cilicia, that is, in the classical Cilicia Tracheia/Cilicia Aspera.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny

  • Hyrcanius Campus
    The modern Manisa Ovası (Manisa plain) in Turkey stretches to the north, west, and east of the modern city of Manisa (ancient Magnesia ad Sipylum). The plain surrounds the confluences of the Hyllos (modern Demirci Çay) and Pidasos (a tributary of Kum Çay) rivers with the Hermus (modern Gediz).

  • Kalhu Archive 1
    Two eighth-century-B.C. archives were excavated in Fort Shalmaneser, a building complex in the southeastern corner of the city Kalhu. One archive was located in Rooms NE 47–50 at the northern side of the northeast courtyard. It consists of about eighty unsealed administrative texts, including twenty-two horse lists and forty-eight wine lists. A few clay tablets were also found in other rooms nearby.
    Creators: Thomas Seidler
    Contributors:
    Modifications: edited; edited; edited; edited; edited; Initial revision; Create; modified Plan location of Kalhu Archive 1 (Create, edited, Initial revision); modified name "Kalhu Archive 1" (Create, edited, Initial revision); modified connection "Fort Shalmaneser" (Create, edited, Initial revision); modified connection "Nimrud" (Create, edited, Initial revision)
    Actors: Thomas Seidler
  • Kalhu Archive 2
    Two eighth-century-B.C. archives were excavated in Fort Shalmaneser, a building complex in the southeastern corner of the city Kalhu. Eleven tablets were found in Room SW 6, a wine store. The archive contains wine lists, as well as notes about the delivery of wine to the palace.
    Creators: Thomas Seidler
    Contributors:
    Modifications: edited; Initial revision; Create; modified Plan location of Kalhu Archive 2 (Create, edited, Initial revision); modified name "Kalhu Archive 2" (Create, Initial revision); modified connection "Fort Shalmaneser" (Create, Initial revision); modified connection "Nimrud" (Create, Initial revision)
    Actors: Thomas Seidler
  • Kalhu Archive 3
    Three seventh-century-B.C. archives were excavated in Fort Shalmaneser, a building complex in the southeastern corner of the city Kalhu. In the northern corner of the south courtyard, mostly in Rooms SE 1 and SE 10, British excavators discovered the archive of the rab ēkalli (“palace manager”). The archive consists of twenty-seven tablets, most of which are sealed. These documents are concerned with the rab ēkalli’s work as manager. The sealed clay bulla were attached to wooden objects such as boxes or writing boards and secured with a string.
    Creators: Thomas Seidler
    Contributors:
    Modifications: edited; edited; edited; edited; edited; Initial revision; Create; modified Plan location of Kalhu Archive 3 (Create, Initial revision); modified name "Kalhu Archive 3" (Create, edited, Initial revision); modified connection "Fort Shalmaneser" (Create, Initial revision); modified connection "Nimrud" (Create, Initial revision)
    Actors: Thomas Seidler
  • Kalhu Archive 4
    Three seventh-century-B.C. archives were excavated in Fort Shalmaneser, a building complex in the southeastern corner of the city Kalhu. The archive from Rooms SE 14–15 consists of nineteen clay tablets, mostly purchase documents but also some loan documents, a release documents, a legal settlement, and a letter. One of the loan documents is written in Neo-Babylonian dialect, instead of the usual Neo-Assyrian dialect.
    Creators: Thomas Seidler
    Contributors:
    Modifications: edited; Initial revision; Create; modified Plan location of Kalhu Archive 4 (Create, Initial revision); modified name "Kalhu Archive 4" (Create, edited, Initial revision); modified connection "Fort Shalmaneser" (Create, Initial revision); modified connection "Nimrud" (Create, edited, Initial revision)
    Actors: Thomas Seidler
  • Kalhu Archive 5
    Three seventh-century-B.C. archives were excavated in Fort Shalmaneser, a building complex in the southeastern corner of the city Kalhu. In Room S 10, in the inner southern part of the palace, British excavators found the archive of the queen's household and of her šakintu (“woman manager”). The archive consists of eighteen clay tablets; most of the documents are sealed. The principal text categories found here are purchase documents, loans, and lawsuits.
    Creators: Thomas Seidler
    Contributors:
    Modifications: edited; edited; Initial revision; Create; modified Plan location of Kalhu Archive 5 (Create, Initial revision); modified name "Kalhu Archive 5" (Create, edited, Initial revision); modified connection "Fort Shalmaneser" (Create, Initial revision); modified connection "Nimrud" (Create, Initial revision)
    Actors: Thomas Seidler
  • Kalhu Archive 6
    Most documents found in the Northwest Palace, built by the Assyrian king Ashurnarsipal II (883–859 BC), predate the move of the new Assyrian capital to Dur-Šarrukin under Sargon II (721–705 BC). Four hundred clay tablets dating to the reign of Sargon II and some of his predecessors were found in Room ZT 4, on the northern side of the northernmost courtyard of the palace. That archive consists of letters to and from the Assyrian king, administrative texts, lists, short notes, records of payments, and one literary text. There were also two rows of open brick boxes in that room of the Northwest Palace; these might have been intended for the storage of clay tablets.
    Creators: Thomas Seidler
    Contributors:
    Modifications: edited; Initial revision; Create; modified Plan location of Kalhu Archive 6 (Create, Initial revision); modified name "Kalhu Archive 6" (Create, Initial revision); modified connection "Northwest Palace at Kalhu" (Create, Initial revision); modified connection "Nimrud" (Create, Initial revision)
    Actors: Thomas Seidler

  • Korydela (island)
    According to a fragment of Favorinus quoted by Stephanus of Byzantium, Korydela was one of two islets that constituted the "Chelidoniai petrai". These "rocks" are thought to be identifiable with the largest two of several islets that lie off modern Cape Gelidonya on the south coast of Anatolia (the modern Beş Adalar = Five Islands). Korydela is identified with the closed of the group to the cape, modern Meşe Adası.
    Creators: C. Foss; S. Mitchell
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; R. Talbert
    Modifications: summary; added FHG, StByz, DFHG; cleaned up references; created OSM location; modified connection "Chelidoniae (islands)" (evidence, regional)
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker; Tom Elliott

  • ‘Locidae Regi’
    ‘Locidae Regi’ is attested on the Peutinger Map, but there is little clarity as to whether it describes the name of a tribal group or of a region. Talbert indicates that Konrad Miller favored a reading that took the term as two words, i.e., "Locidae Regi" instead of as one word, i.e. "Locideregi". The evidence from the Peutinger Map does not offer the chance for a definitive determination.
    Creators: A.G. Poulter
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Ryan Horne; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; R. Talbert; Richard Talbert
    Modifications: modified BAtlas Map Label Location (Submit for review)
    Actors: Tom Elliott

  • Marrucini
    The Marrucini were an Italic tribe centered around Teate in the Abruzzo. In conflict with Rome through the end of the Second Samnite War, the Marrucini became allied with Rome thereafter. Their language was likely in the Sabellic family.

  • Melanippeia (island)
    According to a fragment of Favorinus quoted by Stephanus of Byzantium, Melanippeia was one of two islets that constituted the "Chelidoniai petrai". These "rocks" are thought to be identifiable with the largest two of several islets that lie off modern Cape Gelidonya on the south coast of Anatolia (the modern Beş Adalar = Five Islands). Melanippeia is perhaps to be identified with the largest of the group, modern Devecitaşı Ada.
    Creators: C. Foss; S. Mitchell
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Ryan Horne; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; R. Talbert
    Modifications: added GGM reference and removed erroneous supposition in details; summary; summary; details; title; added FGM, DFGM, and StByz references; removed erroneous GGM reference; created OSM Location; modified name "Melanippeia" (certain, greek, Baseline created, StByz); modified connection "Chelidoniae (islands)" (added StByz, Baseline created, part of regional)
    Actors: Tom Elliott

  • Mesopotamia (region)
    An important region surrounding the Tigris–Euphrates river system, in the northern part of the Fertile Crescent, roughly corresponding to most of modern Iraq and Kuwait, eastern Syria, and Southeastern Turkey. Mesopotamia was a critical part of many empires and kingdoms, including the Sumerians, Akkadians, Assyrians, Babylonians, the Achaemenids, Alexander the Great, and the Seleucids. It was also a site of intense conflict between the Roman, Parthian, and Sassanid Empires until the 7th century Muslim conquest.
    Creators: M. Roaf; S.E. Kroll; St J. Simpson; T. Sinclair
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Ryan Horne; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; R. Talbert; Richard Talbert
    Modifications: created BAtlas Map Label Location
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker; Tom Elliott
  • Messapii

  • Numidia (region)
    Numidia was an ancient region of North Africa. From the late third century B.C. to 40 B.C. the territory was controlled by the ancient kingdom of the Numidians. It later became a Roman client state. Numidia was located in what is now Algeria, as well as parts of Tunisia and Libya in the Maghreb. In pre-Roman terms the polity was divided between the Massylii in the east and the Masaesyli in the west.
    Creators: E.W.B. Fentress
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Michael Heubel; Ryan Horne; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; R. Talbert; R. Warner; Richard Talbert

  • Paeligni
    An ancient Oscan tribe of eastern Italy, the Paeligni are mentioned in the historical sources first in the fourth century BC when they oppose Rome during the Second Samnite War. The Paeligni came into alliance with Rome at the end of the fourth century BC but again took sides against Rome in the Social War.
    Creators: W.V. Harris

  • Rhapta
    A city and trading port on the east coast of Africa, mentioned in the Periplus of the Erythraean Sea and other sources. Probably to be located in the area south of modern Dar es-Salaam, in or around the Rufiji Delta and Mafia archipelago (Tanzania). Rhapta's location has not been archaeologically verified, but monumental architecture identified in 2016 off the north coast of Mafia island is a strong candidate.
    Creators: D.T. Potts
    Contributors: Brady Kiesling; Jeffrey Becker; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; DARMC; Matt Elliott; R. Talbert
    Modifications: summary; creators; added Blundon 2016, Chami 2021, Ryano 2021; added locations based on Blundon, Chami, and Ryano; created Imagery location of submerged site; created Geonames location of Rufiji River Delta; created OSM Location of Mafia archipelago
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker; Tom Elliott

  • Samnium (region)
    Samnium is the Latin name for a region of south and central Italy inhabited by the Samnites. The geographic limits of this region prior to sustained Roman contact are poorly defined. With the Augustan reorganization of Italy, the pre-Roman Samnium is subdivided among three of the Augustan regions.
    Creators: N. Purcell
    Contributors: Brady Kiesling; Jeffrey Becker; Michael Heubel; Ryan Horne; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; R. Talbert; Richard Talbert
    Modifications: created BAtlas Map Label Location

  • Vangiones
    The Vangiones were a Germanic tribe. They allied themselves with Ariovistus (58 BC) as he invaded Gaul and was defeated by Julius Caesar near Belfort. Drusus established two forts among the Vangiones, castrum Mogontiacum (13 BC, later Mainz) and another (14 BC) at Worms.
    Creators: C. Haselgrove; J. Kunow
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Michael Heubel; Ryan Horne; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; R. Talbert; Richard Talbert

  • Via Portuensis?
    The Via Portuensis is an ancient Roman road that connected Rome and Portus. It proceeded along the right bank of the Tiber river, starting from the Pons Aemilius. In the first part of its course it is identical to the Via Campana.
    Creators: L. Quilici and S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; R. Talbert
    Modifications: vici.org 38516: Via Portuensis
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker
  • Vicus Augustanus Laurentium?
    The Vicus Augustanus Laurentium is an ancient settlement in coastal Latium located between the shore and the Via Severiana. The site was first described by Rodolfo Lanciani in 1903. The British School at Rome carried out excavations in the 1980s.
    Creators: L. Quilici; S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; DARMC; R. Talbert
    Modifications: vici.org 62866: Villa Imperiale di Tor Paterno
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker

  • Villa della Longarina

  • Villa di Fralana
    The remains of the so-called villa of Fralana belong to the villa rustica type. Mosaic floors have been discovered at the site, in addition to a productive area that may have included a Torcularium.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors: Tom Elliott
    Modifications: wikidata Q109456874: Villa of Fralana; vici.org 58282: Villa di Fralana
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker
  • Villas at Castelporziano
    The 6,000 ha estate at Castelporziano has been, since antiquity, an elite seaside compound. Where a modern pleasure villa for the Italian president now sits are remains of Roman villas of the Laurentine shore; these remains have been the object of continued study since 1983.
    Creators: L. Quilici; S. Quilici Gigli
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker; Sean Gillies; Tom Elliott; DARMC; R. Talbert
    Modifications: update references
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker

  • Volsci
    The Volsci (Volscians) were an Italic tribe of central Italy during the first millennium B.C. They inhabited parts of southern Latium and were bounded by other tribes, including the Aurunci, Samnites, and Hernici.
